{"id": 12, "ts": 1778943544.070799, "event": "public_discussion_message", "round": 1, "agent": "agent_2", "message": "**Current evidence summary**\n| Candidate | Strengths (relevant to long\u2011distance pilot) | Weaknesses / Concerns |\n|-----------|--------------------------------------------|-----------------------|\n| **A** | \u2022 Anticipates dangerous situations<br>\u2022 Sees complex connections<br>\u2022 Excellent spatial vision<br>\u2022 Very good leadership qualities | \u2022 Regarded as a show\u2011off and not open to new ideas (may affect crew morale and learning)<br>\u2022 No explicit information on calmness under pressure or on communication/teamwork (only indirect hints from leadership and difficulty taking criticism) |\n| **B** | \u2022 Very conscientious (reliability)<br>\u2022 Handles stress very well (calm under pressure)<br>\u2022 Good at assessing weather conditions (technical)<br>\u2022 Excellent computer skills | \u2022 Relatively weak memory for numbers<br>\u2022 Makes nasty remarks about colleagues and can be uncooperative (serious teamwork/communication risk) |\n| **C** | \u2022 Keeps calm in a crisis (strong composure)<br>\u2022 Can make correct decisions quickly (decision\u2011making)<br>\u2022 Understands complicated technology (technical competence) | \u2022 Difficulty communicating ideas (teamwork risk)<br>\u2022 Regarded as egocentric (crew cooperation)<br>\u2022 Not very willing to further his education (long\u2011term development) |\n| **D** | \u2022 Responds adequately to unexpected events (some pressure handling)<br>\u2022 Concentrates very well<br>\u2022 Solves problems extremely well (technical/problem\u2011solving)<br>\u2022 Takes responsibility seriously (reliability) | \u2022 Hot temper, considered moody, regarded as a loner, and seen as a \u201cknow\u2011it\u2011all\u201d (potentially harmful to crew dynamics) |\n**Key gaps that could shift the assessment**\n* **Candidate A** \u2013 We still lack any direct evidence of how A behaves under high\u2011pressure situations and how he communicates with a crew.\n* **Candidate C** \u2013 While we know he struggles to communicate ideas, we have no further detail on his ability to work within a crew, accept feedback, or resolve interpersonal conflict.\n* **Candidate D** \u2013 Apart from the negative interpersonal descriptors, we have no concrete examples of his teamwork or communication style.\n**Preliminary weighting**\nLong\u2011distance operations place the highest premium on calmness under pressure, sound decision\u2011making, and effective crew coordination.\n* **Calmness/Decision\u2011making:** C (calm in crisis, quick correct decisions) > B (handles stress well) > D (adequate response) > A (no data).\n* **Technical competence:** A (spatial vision, anticipation), C (technology), D (problem solving), B (weather, computers).\n* **Reliability/Responsibility:** B (conscientious), D (takes responsibility), A (leadership), C (less evidence).\n* **Teamwork/Communication:** All have notable concerns; B\u2019s uncooperative attitude and nasty remarks appear most severe, D\u2019s hot temper and loner reputation are also serious, A\u2019s show\u2011off attitude and resistance to new ideas could erode crew trust, while C\u2019s difficulty communicating and egocentric view directly affect crew coordination.\nBalancing these, **Candidate C** offers the strongest combination of calmness and rapid, correct decision\u2011making\u2014critical for handling long\u2011haul emergencies\u2014while his technical understanding is solid. The primary drawback is his communication difficulty, which, if mitigated through targeted crew\u2011resource\u2011training, may be less fatal than the interpersonal hostility shown by B or the temperament issues of D.\n**What would change my view**\n* Any positive, concrete evidence of A\u2019s composure under pressure or effective crew communication.\n* Evidence that C\u2019s communication issues are minor or that he actively seeks crew input and resolves conflicts.\n* Information showing D can work constructively with a crew despite his temperament.\n* Confirmation that B\u2019s uncooperative behavior is isolated rather than systemic.\n**Current provisional vote:** Candidate C, with moderate confidence (\u224860\u202f%). I remain open to revising this assessment pending additional information on the highlighted gaps.\nMETADATA_JSON:\n{\"agent\": \"agent_2\", \"vote\": \"Candidate C\"}", "thoughts": "We have gathered info from other agents about A, D, B. Need also info about C's calmness under pressure, teamwork/communication, etc. Also need other attributes for each candidate: we have many facts already. Let's compile all known facts.\n\nFrom problem statement:\n\nCandidate A:\n- can anticipate dangerous situations.\n- able to see complex connections.\n- excellent spatial vision.\n- very good leadership qualities.\n- regarded as a show-off.\n- regarded as being not open to new ideas.\n\nCandidate B:\n- very conscientious.\n- handles stress very well.\n- good at assessing weather conditions.\n- excellent computer skills.\n- relatively weak memory for numbers.\n- makes nasty remarks about his colleagues.\n\nCandidate C:\n- can make correct decisions quickly.\n- has difficulty communicating ideas.\n- is regarded as egocentric.\n- not very willing to further his education.\n- keeps calm in a crisis.\n- understands complicated technology.\n\nCandidate D:\n- responds to unexpected events adequately.\n- can concentrate very well.\n- solves problems extremely well.\n- takes responsibility seriously.\n- regarded as a know-it-all.\n- has a hot temper.\n\nAlso from earlier: Candidate B handles stress very well (already). Candidate B makes nasty remarks about colleagues (negative for teamwork). Candidate B has weak memory for numbers (maybe less relevant). Candidate B excellent computer skills (technical). Candidate B good at assessing weather (technical). Candidate B very conscientious (reliability